entry.title: [Office] Fix disabling multiple ODFS volumes
entry.content:
Disabling a volume on the UI involves removing the associated item from

the directory tree so that it can be redrawn. To do so, we were using a

`for of` loop to find and remove the disabled volume from the tree.



The array iterator used in a `for of` loop increments an array index

to select the next element to iterate on. When an element is removed

from the array during the iteration, the next element (which we may

want to remove too) can therefore be skipped.



Replace the `for of` loop with a regular `for` loop so that the

current iteration index can be controlled.



Bug: b:293547300

entry.content:
This CL lets LoginDisplayHost calls completion_callbacks_ added from

Finalize or StartUserAdding immediately on destruction for all derived

classes by followings:

We should call completion_callback_ immediately instead of posting to

SingleThreadTaskRunner for LoginDisplayHostCommon, but we need to fix

UserAddingScreen ownership beforehand which will be done in the next cl.

completion_callbacks_ asynchrounsly does not cause a memory leak.

entry.title: Prevent decoding of percent-encoded ASCII characters in URL's path
entry.content:
This CL is part of the URL interop 2023 effort. "Intent to Implement

and Ship" is [1].



Currently, when Chrome parses a URL, it decodes percent-encoded ASCII

characters in URL path. However, this behavior doesn't align with the

URL Standard [2]. The CL fixes this behavior to retain percent-encoded

ASCII characters in URL's path.



Before:



> const url = new URL("http://example.com/%41");

> url.href

"http://example.com/A"



After:



> const url = new URL("http://example.com/%41");

> url.href

"http://example.com/%41"



Interoperability:



- Chrome isn't compliant, while Firefox and Safari are compliant.

- I've tested URL APIs in non-browser environments and libraries,

such as Deno's `URL` implementation [3] and Rust's `url` crate [4],

both of which are standard-compliant.



Background:



The existing behavior seems to be a result of past decisions. The

comment in `url_canon_path.cc` states:



> // This table was used to be designed to match exactly what IE did

> // with the characters.



Impact:



Regarding implementation, web-exported URL APIs, GURL, and KURL share

the same URL parser and canonicalization backend. Given that these URL

classes are widely used both internally or externally, predicting all

possible consequences and risks is challenging.



Given the very low user metrics [5], we received approval to land [1],

but with a kill switch in place.



UMA:



Usage: 0.000071% (URL.Path.UnescapeEscapedChar [5], as of Aug 2023)



This number isn't specific to any particular use case and represents a

an upper bound. The actual impact is likely lower.



Interaction with web servers:



Before:



When a user enters "https://example.com/%41" in the address bar or

clicks a link like , Chrome sends

"/A" to the server.



After::



Chrome now sends "/%41" to the server, without decoding, similar to

Safari and Firefox. Note that Chrome's address bar will still display

"https://example.com/A" because the address bar formats URLs in their

own way.



For websites, how to handle percent-encoded characters in a URL's path

is up to each website. Since they can receive such URLs from various

clients, not just Chrome, this isn't a new issue for most websites.

They typically decode a URL's path before processing.



Another concern relates to Chromium's internal code or developers who

rely on the current behavior, intentionally or not.



For example, this CL might lead to issues in cases like:



```

const hash = {};



const url1 = new URL("http://example.com/%41");

hash[url1.href] = "v1";

// ...

const url2 = new URL("http://example.com/A");

hash[url2.href] // Assumed that "v1" is retrieved, but this is no longer true.

```



According to the URL Standard, `url1` and `url2` are not equivalent

[6], but some clients might depend on Chrome's current behavior as a

feature. This presents a risk.



Additional notes:



- This change only affects the URL's path. Other parts like the host

are not impacted.

- There was a discussion about Chrome's behavior [7]. The consensus is

that Chrome's behavior should be fixed for better interoperability.

- There's a proposal to add a normalization interface [8] to URL.

entry.title: pip-pinch: Reuse component value during gesture transitions
entry.content:
This commit makes sure that the `window_component` is set properly with

gesture transitions when the first gesture is started by the client.

The pinch-to-resize feature handles gesture transitions (i.e. drag to

pinch and vice versa). The same `window_component` should be used from

when the first finger touches the screen to when the last finger leaves

the screen. Usually when a gesture is started by the client, the client

specifies the window_component to be used for the rest of the gesture.

However, when a gesture is not initiated but instead is transitioned

from another, new gestures were initiated by `ToplevelWindowHandler`

using the incorrect `window_component`.



To fix this, `ToplevelWindowEventHandler` now keeps track of the first

gesture’s `window_component` and it’s now reused until all of the

gestures end.

entry.title: Fenced frame: fix tab focus not passing to Chrome.
entry.content:
When a frame receives an "initial focus" call, it behaves differently

than subsequent focus calls. One difference is that the frame will not

attempt to pass focus back to Chrome if it has no focusable elements[1].

It determines whether a focus is an initial focus simply by checking if

there is a source frame for the focus call[2]. A fenced frame does not

get this information as that can allow it to learn about its embedder.

As a side effect, every time focus is passed to a fenced frame, it

treats the focus call as an initial focus. So, if there is a fenced

frame with no focusable elements, if it receives a -focus event, it

will not pass focus back to Chrome to give to the next frame if there is

nothing that can be focused. Instead, it will "bounce" focus back to its

owner. This means that focus will be blocked from going past the fenced

frame to the next element after the fenced frame.



Since a fenced frame always gets "initial focus", this CL has fenced

frames always attempt to pass focus to Chrome if they have no focusable

elements. This CL also enables 2 focus-related browser tests that were

disabled due to this bug.



No spec changes are needed as part of this change. The focusing part of

the spec has no concept of an "initial focus"; that is a Chromium-

specific implementation detail. See the design document for a deeper

explanation.



Design document: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1jZAtIzTqfbzOUuyLdXlItGXb_UUyB7YE_QG4EOTy0nc/edit?usp=sharing&resourcekey=0-O5ZLaN1prgeEgBxWd-JXTA



[1]https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/renderer/core/page/focus_controller.cc;l=1139;drc=906a07cd56b97f3376d21b46dd8d9537bd2aa0ea

[2]https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/renderer/core/frame/local_frame_mojo_handler.cc;l=703-706;drc=a056443eb4e1a5922ce82b2d11a7b4e64e01f5a6

entry.title: [DoH] Add metric to better report auto-upgrade success
entry.content:
This CL adds a new metric that reports the state of the insecure DNS

to secure DNS auto-upgrade process one minute after this process

begins. This should provide a more direct way of identifying whether

the auto-upgrade functionality should be enabled for a given provider.



Also, this CL extends the expiration times of several other metrics

that we are considering replacing by this new metric (and extends the

expiration of Net.DNS.DnsTransaction.SecureNotValidated...FailureError

to match the set of those metrics that we plan to keep longer term.)
